                    </div>
                    <span>Overall the book is good. I prefer the "The CISSP Prep Guide: Gold Edition by Wiley" for CISSP exam preparation. However Shon Harris's coverage of cryptography is excelent. The book font is small, which makes it hard to read. Also Shon sometimes tend to repeat things.</span>
                  
                    <div class="CustomerReviewSummary">Easy read but some inaccuracies </div>
                    <div>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Rating: </span>
                      <span>3</span>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Helpful: </span>
                      <span>0</span>
                      /
                      <span>1</span>
                      votes <span class="ItemCaption">Reviewed: </span>
                      <span>2005-03-16</span>
                    </div>
                    <span>Shon Harris describes the material in an easy to read style, but I soon noticed that she doesn't always know what she is talking about. An entertaining style can be great, as e.g. in Tannenbaum's classic book on Computer Networks, because Tannenbaum knows what he talks about. After having read a few chapters of Harris' book, I noticed that she sometimes guesses meanings, e.g. when she describes Authorization to be that the system has granted the user access to a resource, which of course is wrong. That's worrisome when you want to prepare for an exam. The verbose style is also not very efficient for describing lots of specific details and concepts, so that the book contains less of that than some of the other CISSP books.</span>
                  
                    <div class="CustomerReviewSummary">This is Junk</div>
